.TH RUNBOOK 1 "March 2026" "version 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
runbook \- personal command center and runbook engine
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B runbook
.I command
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
[\fIarguments\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B runbook
defines, manages, and executes multi-step operational runbooks from YAML
definitions. Steps can run local shell commands, SSH into remote hosts, or
make HTTP requests. Variables are passed between steps, and error policies
control execution flow.
.PP
Runbooks are discovered from \fB~/.runbook/books/\fR by default and from
the current directory. Each runbook is a YAML file defining a name,
optional variables, and an ordered list of steps.
.PP
Steps support per-step timeouts, error handling policies (abort, continue,
retry), conditional execution via Go template expressions, confirmation
prompts, and output capture into variables for use in later steps.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B run \fI<name|path>\fR
Execute a runbook. Looks up by name in the runbook directory, by filename,
or by direct file path.
.TP
.B list
List all discovered runbooks from the configured directory and current
working directory.
.TP
.B show \fI<name|path>\fR
Print runbook details including variables, steps, types, and step
configuration (timeouts, error policies, capture targets).
.TP
.B validate \fI<name|path>\fR
Parse and validate a runbook without executing it. Reports structural
errors such as missing names, invalid step types, or misconfigured
retry policies.
.TP
.B history
Show runbook execution history. Each run is saved as a JSON file in
\fB~/.runbook/history/\fR with per-step timing and status.
.TP
.B auth \fI<name|path>\fR
Pre-resolve and cache 1Password secrets in the system keychain.
Scans the runbook for variables with \fBop://\fR default values and
resolves them via the 1Password CLI. Use \fB--clear\fR to remove
cached secrets.
.TP
.B pull \fI<repo-url|file-url>\fR
Clone a git repository into \fB~/.runbook/books/\fR so its YAML files
become discoverable. If previously pulled, updates to the latest version.
Also supports downloading a single YAML file by URL.
.TP
.B pull list
List pulled repositories and their runbook counts.
.TP
.B pull remove \fI<name>\fR
Remove a previously pulled repository.
.TP
.B cron add \fI<name|path>\fR \fI<schedule>\fR
Add a crontab entry to run a runbook on a schedule. The schedule uses
standard cron syntax (5 fields: minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week).
Output is logged to \fB~/.runbook/history/<name>.log\fR.
.TP
.B cron list
List all runbook-managed crontab entries.
.TP
.B cron remove \fI<name>\fR
Remove a scheduled runbook from crontab.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Global Options
.TP
.BR \-\-dir " \fIDIR\fR"
Override the runbook directory. Default: \fB~/.runbook/books/\fR.
.SS Run Options
.TP
.BR \-\-var " \fIkey=value\fR"
Set a variable for the run. Can be specified multiple times. Overrides
defaults and environment variables.
.TP
.BR \-\-dry\-run
Validate and display the runbook, variables, and steps without executing.
.TP
.BR \-\-yes
Auto-confirm all confirmation prompts.
.TP
.BR \-\-no\-tui
Disable TUI mode and use plain streaming output.
.SS History Options
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-limit " \fIN\fR"
Maximum number of records to show. Default: 20.
.TP
.BR \-\-runbook " \fINAME\fR"
Filter history by runbook name.
.SS Auth Options
.TP
.BR \-\-clear
Remove cached secrets from the system keychain instead of resolving.
.SS Cron Schedule Syntax
Standard cron format with 5 fields:
.PP
.RS
minute (0-59) hour (0-23) day-of-month (1-31) month (1-12) day-of-week (0-7)
.RE
.PP
Examples: \fB"0 3 * * 0"\fR (Sundays at 3am), \fB"*/15 * * * *"\fR (every 15 min),
\fB"30 2 * * 1-5"\fR (weekdays at 2:30am).
.SH VARIABLES
Variables can be defined in runbook YAML with defaults, required flags, and
interactive prompts. Values are resolved in priority order:
.PP
.RS
1. YAML default value (lowest priority)
.br
2. Environment variable \fBRUNBOOK_VAR_<NAME>\fR
.br
3. CLI \fB\-\-var\fR flag (highest priority)
.RE
.PP
Variable references use Go template syntax: \fB{{.varname}}\fR. All string
fields in steps (command, URL, body, headers, confirm) are template-expanded
before execution.
.SH STEP TYPES
.TP
.B shell
Run a local shell command via \fBsh -c\fR. Supports \fBcommand\fR and
optional \fBdir\fR fields.
.TP
.B ssh
Run a command on a remote host via SSH. Supports \fBhost\fR, \fBuser\fR,
\fBport\fR, \fBkey_file\fR, \fBcommand\fR, and \fBagent_auth\fR fields.
.TP
.B http
Make an HTTP request. Supports \fBmethod\fR, \fBurl\fR, \fBheaders\fR,
and \fBbody\fR fields.
.SH STEP FEATURES
.TP
.B capture
Store stdout (shell/ssh) or response body (http) into a named variable.
.TP
.B condition
Go template expression. Step runs only if it renders to \fB"true"\fR.
.TP
.B on_error
Error policy: \fBabort\fR (default), \fBcontinue\fR, or \fBretry\fR.
.TP
.B retries
Maximum retry count when on_error is \fBretry\fR.
.TP
.B timeout
Per-step timeout as a duration string (e.g., \fB30s\fR, \fB5m\fR).
.TP
.B confirm
Prompt the user before executing. Template-expanded.
.TP
.B parallel
When consecutive steps have \fBparallel: true\fR, they run concurrently.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B runbook run deploy.yaml
Execute the deploy.yaml runbook in the current directory.
.TP
.B runbook run \-\-var version=1.2.3 deploy
Find and run the "deploy" runbook, setting the version variable.
.TP
.B runbook run \-\-yes \-\-var host=web01 restart-services
Run with auto-confirmed prompts and a host override.
.TP
.B runbook run \-\-dry\-run deploy.yaml
Show what would be executed without running anything.
.TP
.B runbook list
List all available runbooks.
.TP
.B runbook show deploy
Display details of the deploy runbook.
.TP
.B runbook validate deploy.yaml
Validate the runbook structure without executing.
.TP
.B runbook history
Show recent run history.
.TP
.B runbook history \-n 5 \-\-runbook deploy
Show last 5 runs of the deploy runbook.
.TP
.B runbook auth deploy
Pre-cache 1Password secrets for the deploy runbook.
.TP
.B runbook auth \-\-clear deploy
Remove cached secrets for the deploy runbook.
.TP
.B runbook pull github.com/user/runbooks
Pull runbooks from a git repository.
.TP
.B runbook pull https://example.com/deploy.yaml
Download a single runbook file.
.TP
.B runbook cron add update-pihole "0 3 * * 0"
Schedule the update-pihole runbook to run every Sunday at 3:00 AM.
.TP
.B runbook cron list
List all scheduled runbooks.
.TP
.B runbook cron remove update-pihole
Remove the update-pihole schedule.
.SH 1PASSWORD SECRETS
Variables with \fBop://\fR default values (e.g., \fBop://Vault/Item/field\fR)
are resolved through the 1Password CLI (\fBop read\fR) and cached in the
system keychain. This allows runbooks to reference secrets without storing
them in plaintext YAML files.
.PP
Use \fBrunbook auth <name>\fR to pre-cache secrets before running, or let
them be resolved automatically on first run. Cached values persist in the
system keychain until explicitly cleared.
.PP
Supported keychains: macOS Keychain, GNOME Secret Service (Linux),
Windows Credential Manager.
.SH NOTIFICATIONS
Runbooks can send notifications after completion via a \fBnotify\fR section
in the YAML definition.
.PP
Supported channels:
.TP
.B slack
Post to a Slack incoming webhook. The \fBwebhook\fR field can be an
\fBop://\fR reference. Optional \fBchannel\fR overrides the default.
.TP
.B desktop
Show a native OS notification. Uses \fBosascript\fR on macOS,
\fBnotify-send\fR on Linux, and Windows toast notifications via PowerShell.
.TP
.B email
Send an email via SMTP. Supports \fBto\fR, \fBfrom\fR, \fBhost\fR
(host:port), \fBusername\fR, and \fBpassword\fR (supports \fBop://\fR).
.PP
The \fBon\fR field controls when to notify: \fBalways\fR (default),
\fBfailure\fR, or \fBsuccess\fR.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success. All steps completed or the command finished without error.
.TP
.B 1
An error occurred. A step failed with abort policy, validation failed,
or the runbook was not found.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B ~/.runbook/books/
Default directory for runbook YAML files.
.TP
.B ~/.runbook/history/
Run history storage (JSON files, one per execution).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B RUNBOOK_VAR_<NAME>
Set a runbook variable via environment. The variable name is uppercased.
For example, \fBRUNBOOK_VAR_HOST=prod01\fR sets the \fBhost\fR variable.
